[src:d3js/api-svgelement] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] All of the SVG DOM interfaces that correspond directly to elements in the SVG language derive from the `SVGElement` interface.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] A `StylePropertyMap` representing the declarations of the element's `style` attribute.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Whether the control should be focused when the page loads, or when a `<dialog>` or popover become shown.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] An `SVGAnimatedString` that reflects the value of the `class` attribute on the given element, or the empty string if `class` is not present.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] This attribute is deprecated and may be removed in a future version of this specification.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Authors are advised to use `Element.classList` instead.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] A `DOMStringMap` object which provides a list of key/value pairs of named data attributes which correspond to custom data attributes attached to the element.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] These can also be defined in SVG using attributes of the form `data-*`, where `*` is the key name for the pair.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] This works just like HTML's `HTMLElement.dataset` property and HTML's `data-*` global attribute.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Returns the cryptographic number used once that is used by Content Security Policy to determine whether a given fetch will be allowed to proceed.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] An `SVGSVGElement` referring to the nearest ancestor `<svg>` element.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] `null` if the given element is the outermost `<svg>` element.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] A `CSSStyleDeclaration` representing the declarations of the element's `style` attribute.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] The position of the element in the tabbing order.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] The `SVGElement` which established the current viewport.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Often the nearest ancestor `<svg>` element.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Removes keyboard focus from the currently focused element.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Makes the element the current keyboard focus.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the equivalent `on...` handler property.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Fired when page loading is stopped before an SVG element has been allowed to load completely.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Fired when an SVG element does not load properly or when an error occurs during script execution.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Fires on an `SVGElement` when it is loaded in the browser.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Fired when an SVG document is being resized.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Fired when an SVG document view is being shifted along the X and/or Y axes.
[src:d3js/api-svgelement] Fired when the DOM implementation removes an SVG document from a window or frame.
[src:d3js/d3-js] There have been various previous attempts to bring data visualization to web browsers.
[src:d3js/d3-js] The most notable examples were the Prefuse, Flare, and Protovis toolkits, which can all be considered as direct predecessors of D3.js.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Prefuse was a visualization toolkit created in 2005 that required usage of Java, and visualizations were rendered within browsers with a Java plug-in.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Flare was a similar toolkit from 2007 that used ActionScript, and required a Flash plug-in for rendering.
[src:d3js/d3-js] In 2009, based on the experience of developing and utilizing Prefuse and Flare, Jeffrey Heer, Mike Bostock, and Vadim Ogievetsky of Stanford University's Stanford Visualization Group created Protovis, a JavaScript library to generate SVG graphics from data.
[src:d3js/d3-js] The library was known to data visualization practitioners and academics.
[src:d3js/d3-js] In 2011, the development of Protovis was stopped to focus on a new project, D3.js.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Informed by experiences with Protovis, Bostock, along with Heer and Ogievetsky, developed D3.js to provide a more expressive framework that, at the same time, focuses on web standards and provides improved performance.
[src:d3js/d3-js] The D3.js library uses pre-built functions to select elements, create SVG objects, style them, or add transitions, dynamic effects, or tooltips.
[src:d3js/d3-js] These objects can also be styled using CSS.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Large datasets can be bound to SVG objects using D3.js functions to generate text/graphic charts and diagrams.
[src:d3js/d3-js] The data can be in various formats such as JSON, comma-separated values (CSV) or geoJSON, but, if required, JavaScript functions can be written to read other data formats.
[src:d3js/d3-js] The central principle of D3.js design is to enable the programmer to first use a CSS-style selector to select a given set of Document Object Model (DOM) nodes, then use operators to manipulate them in a similar manner to jQuery.
[src:d3js/d3-js] The selection can be based on an HTML tag, class, identifier, attribute, or place in the hierarchy.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Once elements are selected, one can apply operations to them.
[src:d3js/d3-js] This includes getting and setting attributes, display texts, and styles (as in the above example).
[src:d3js/d3-js] This process of modifying, creating and removing HTML elements can be made dependent on data, which is the basic concept of D3.js.
[src:d3js/d3-js] By declaring a transition, values for attributes and styles can be smoothly interpolated over a certain time.
[src:d3js/d3-js] For more advanced uses, loaded data drives the creation of elements.
[src:d3js/d3-js] D3.js loads a given dataset, then, for each of its elements, creates an SVG object with associated properties (shape, colors, values) and behaviors (transitions, events).
[src:d3js/d3-js] Generated SVG graphics are designed according to the provided data.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Once a dataset is bound to a document, use of D3.js typically follows a pattern wherein an explicit `.enter()` function, an implicit "update," and an explicit `.exit()` function is invoked for each item in the bound dataset.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Any methods chained after the `.enter()` command will be called for each item in the dataset not already represented by a DOM node in the selection (the previous `selectAll()`).
[src:d3js/d3-js] Likewise, the implicit update function is called on all existing selected nodes for which there is a corresponding item in the dataset, and `.exit()` is called on all existing selected nodes that do not have an item in the dataset to bind to them.
[src:d3js/d3-js] The D3.js documentation provides several examples of how this works.
[src:d3js/d3-js] D3.js is a popular toolset used by many individuals and organizations for data visualization.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Some organizations that use it include The New York Times, Airbnb, and MTV.
[src:d3js/d3-js] Mike Bostock created bl.ocks as a website for sharing D3 visualizations and code snippets, which used GitHub Gist to host the code.
[src:d3js/d3-js] He later created Observable as a place where programmers could make and share visualizations.
[src:d3js/d3-js] (Similar to bl.ocks but the code is all hosted on the observable site).
[src:d3js/d3-js] There are also D3 communities on many programming sites like CodePen.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:d3js/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images are defined in a vector graphics format and stored in XML text files.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can thus be scaled in size without loss of quality, and SVG files can be searched, indexed, scripted, and compressed.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The XML text files can be created and edited with text editors or vector graphics editors, and are rendered by most web browsers.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG can include JavaScript, potentially leading to cross-site scripting.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG has been in development within the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) since 1999 after six competing proposals for vector graphics languages had been submitted to the consortium during 1998 (see below).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The early SVG Working Group decided not to develop any of the commercial submissions, but to create a new markup language that was informed by but not really based on any of them.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The working group was chaired at the time by Chris Lilley of the W3C.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Early adoption was limited due to lack of support in older versions of Internet Explorer.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] However, as of 2011, all major desktop browsers began to support SVG.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Native browser support offers various advantages, such as not requiring plugins, allowing SVG to be mixed with other content, and improving rendering and scripting reliability.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Mobile support for SVG exists in various forms, with different devices and browsers supporting SVG Tiny 1.1 or 1.2.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG can be produced using vector graphics editors and rendered into raster formats.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] In web-based applications, Inline SVG allows embedding SVG content within HTML documents.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The SVG specification was updated to version 1.1 in 2011.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Scalable Vector Graphics 2 became a W3C Candidate Recommendation on 15 September 2016.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG 2 incorporates several new features in addition to those of SVG 1.1 and SVG Tiny 1.2.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG 2 reached the Candidate Recommendation stage on 15 September 2016, and revised versions were published on 7 August 2018 and 4 October 2018.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The latest draft was released on 14 September 2025.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG supports interactivity, animation, and rich graphical capabilities, making it suitable for both web and print applications.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can be compressed with the gzip algorithm, resulting in SVGZ files that are typically 20–50% smaller than the original.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG also supports metadata, enabling better indexing, searching, and retrieval of SVG content.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG allows three types of graphic objects: vector graphic shapes (such as paths consisting of straight lines and curves), bitmap images, and text.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Graphical objects can be grouped, styled, transformed and composited into previously rendered objects.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The feature set includes nested transformations, clipping paths, alpha masks, filter effects and template objects.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG drawings can be interactive and can include animation, defined in the SVG XML elements or via scripting that accesses the SVG Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG uses CSS for styling and JavaScript for scripting.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Text, including internationalization and localization, appearing in plain text within the SVG DOM, enhances the accessibility of SVG graphics.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Though the SVG Specification primarily focuses on vector graphics markup language, its design includes the basic capabilities of a page description language like Adobe's PDF.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] It contains provisions for rich graphics, and is compatible with CSS for styling purposes.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG has the information needed to place each glyph and image in a chosen location on a printed page.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG drawings can be dynamic and interactive.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Time-based modifications to the elements can be described in SMIL, or can be programmed in a scripting language (e.g.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C explicitly recommends SMIL as the standard for animation in SVG.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] A rich set of event handlers such as "onmouseover" and "onclick" can be assigned to any SVG graphical object to apply actions and events.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Because of industry demand, two mobile profiles were introduced with SVG 1.1: *SVG Tiny* (SVGT) and *SVG Basic* (SVGB).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] These are subsets of the full SVG standard, mainly intended for user agents with limited capabilities.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] In particular, SVG Tiny was defined for highly restricted mobile devices such as cellphones; it does not support styling or scripting.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG Basic was defined for higher-level mobile devices, such as smartphones.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] In 2003, the 3GPP, an international telecommunications standards group, adopted SVG Tiny as the mandatory vector graphics media format for next-generation phones.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT is the required vector graphics format and support of SVGB is optional for Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS) and Packet-switched Streaming Service.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] It was later added as required format for vector graphics in 3GPP IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Neither mobile profile includes support for the full Document Object Model (DOM), while only SVG Basic has optional support for scripting, but because they are fully compatible subsets of the full standard, most SVG graphics can still be rendered by devices which only support the mobile profiles.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT 1.2 adds a microDOM (μDOM), styling and scripting.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVGT 1.2 also includes some features not found in SVG 1.1, including non-scaling strokes, which are supported by some SVG 1.1 implementations, such as Opera, Firefox, and WebKit.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] As shared code bases between desktop and mobile browsers increased, the use of SVG 1.1 over SVGT 1.2 also increased.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images, being XML, contain many repeated fragments of text, so they are well suited for lossless data compression algorithms.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] When an SVG image has been compressed with the gzip algorithm, it is referred to as an "SVGZ" image and uses the corresponding `.svgz` filename extension.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Conforming SVG 1.1 viewers will display compressed images.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] An SVGZ file is typically 20 to 50 percent of the original size.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] W3C provides SVGZ files to test for conformance.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] (for "line to") precedes a point to which a line should be drawn.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] In all cases, absolute coordinates follow capital letter commands and relative coordinates are used after the equivalent lower-case letters.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Straight-line paths and paths made up of a series of connected straight-line segments (polylines), as well as closed polygons, circles, and ellipses can be drawn.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Rectangles and round-cornered rectangles are also standard elements.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG shapes can be filled and outlined (painted with a color, a gradient, or a pattern).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Fills may be opaque, or have any degree of transparency.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] "Markers" are line-end features, such as arrowheads, or symbols that can appear at the vertices of a polygon.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG shapes can be filled or outlined with solid colors as above, or with color gradients or with repeating patterns.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Color gradients can be linear or radial (circular), and can involve any number of colors as well as repeats.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Opacity gradients can also be specified.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Gradients and patterns can be animated and scripted.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] could usefully be added to the SVG specification.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The current draft of SVG 2 includes gradient meshes.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] regions that can be painted (with colors, gradients and patterns) independently.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can interact with users in many ways.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] , mouse clicks, scrolling or zooming the image and other pointer, keyboard and document events.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Event handlers may start, stop or alter animations as well as trigger scripts in response to such events.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] can link to SVG files that change the visible area of the document.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] This allows for creating specific view states that are used to zoom in/out of a specific area or to limit the view to a specific element.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] element also allow linking to and re-using internal and external elements.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] This allows coders to do more with less markup and makes for cleaner code.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] All aspects of an SVG document can be accessed and manipulated using scripts in a similar way to HTML.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] (DOM) objects for every SVG element and attribute.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] They can run in response to pointer events, keyboard events and document events as required.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Content can be animated by manipulating the DOM using ECMAScript and the scripting language's built-in timers.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Animations can be continuous, they can loop and repeat, and they can respond to user events, as mentioned above.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] As with HTML and CSS, text in SVG may reference external font files, such as system fonts.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] If the required font files do not exist on the machine where the SVG file is rendered, the text may not appear as intended.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] metadata properties (e.g. title, creator/author, subject, description, etc.).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Other metadata schemas may also be used.
