[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] An SVG document can define components including shapes, gradients etc., and use them repeatedly.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can also contain raster graphics, such as PNG and JPEG images, and further SVG images.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The use of SVG on the web was limited by the lack of support in older versions of Internet Explorer (IE).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Many websites that serve SVG images also provide the images in a raster format, either automatically by HTTP content negotiation or by allowing the user directly to choose the file.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Konqueror was the first browser to support SVG in release version 3.2 in February 2004.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] As of 2011, all major desktop browsers, and many minor ones, have some level of SVG support.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Other browsers' implementations are not yet complete; see comparison of layout engines for further details.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] However, SVG images may be included in XHTML pages using XML namespaces.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, was critical of early versions of Internet Explorer for its failure to support SVG.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] There are several advantages to native and full support: plugins are not needed, SVG can be freely mixed with other content in a single document, and rendering and scripting become considerably more reliable.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Support for SVG may be limited to SVGT on older or more limited smart phones or may be primarily limited by their respective operating system.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Adobe Flash Lite has optionally supported SVG Tiny since version 1.1.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] At the SVG Open 2005 conference, Sun demonstrated a mobile implementation of SVG Tiny 1.1 for the Connected Limited Device Configuration (CLDC) platform.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Mobiles that use Opera Mobile, as well as the iPhone's built in browser, also include SVG support.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] However, even though it used the WebKit engine, the Android built-in browser did not support SVG prior to v3.0 (Honeycomb).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Prior to v3.0, Firefox Mobile 4.0b2 (beta) for Android was the first browser running under Android to support SVG by default.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The level of SVG Tiny support available varies from mobile to mobile, depending on the SVG engine installed.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Many newer mobile products support additional features beyond SVG Tiny 1.1, like gradient and opacity; this is sometimes referred to as "SVGT 1.1+", though there is no such standard.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] RIM's BlackBerry has built-in support for SVG Tiny 1.1 since version 5.0.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Support continues for WebKit-based BlackBerry Torch browser in OS 6 and 7.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Nokia's S60 platform has built-in support for SVG.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] For example, icons are generally rendered using the platform's SVG engine.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Nokia has also led the JSR 226: Scalable 2D Vector Graphics API expert group that defines Java ME API for SVG presentation and manipulation.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] This API has been implemented in S60 Platform 3rd Edition Feature Pack 1 and onward.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Some Series 40 phones also support SVG (such as Nokia 6280).
