[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Phones with Sony Ericsson Java Platform-8 have support for JSR 226.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Windows Phone has supported SVG since version 7.5.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG is also supported on various mobile devices from Motorola, Samsung, LG, and Siemens mobile/BenQ-Siemens. eSVG, an SVG rendering library mainly written for embedded devices, is available on some mobile platforms.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can be hand-coded or produced by the use of a vector graphics editor, such as Inkscape, Adobe Illustrator, Adobe Animate, or CorelDRAW, and rendered to common raster image formats such as PNG using the same software.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Additionally, editors like Inkscape and Boxy SVG provide tools to trace raster images to Bézier curves typically using image tracing back-ends like potrace, autotrace, and imagetracerjs.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Software can be programmed to render SVG images by using a library such as librsvg used by GNOME since 2000, Batik and ThorVG since 2020 for lightweight systems.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG images can also be rendered to any desired popular image format by using ImageMagick, a free command-line utility (which also uses librsvg under the hood).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] For web-based applications, the mode of usage termed Inline SVG allows SVG content to be embedded within an HTML document using an `<svg>` tag.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Its graphical capabilities can then be employed to create sophisticated user interfaces as the SVG and HTML share context, event handling, and CSS.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Other uses for SVG include embedding for use in word processing (e.g. with LibreOffice) and desktop publishing (e.g.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] Scribus), plotting graphs (e.g. gnuplot), and importing paths (e.g. for use in GIMP or Blender).
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The application services Microsoft 365 and Microsoft Office 2019 offer support for exporting, importing and editing SVG images.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The Uniform Type Identifier for SVG used by Apple is `public.svg-image` and conforms to `public.image` and `public.xml`.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] As a document format, similar to HTML documents, SVG can host scripts or CSS.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] This is an issue when an attacker can upload a SVG file, such as a profile picture, to a website and the file is treated as a normal picture, but contains malicious content.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] For instance, if an SVG file is deployed as a CSS background image, or a logo on some website, or in some image gallery, then, when the image is loaded in a browser, it activates a script or other content.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] This could lock up the browser (the Billion laughs attack), but could also lead to HTML injection and cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C therefore stipulates certain requirements when SVG is simply used for images: SVG Security.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The W3C says that Inline SVG (an SVG file loaded natively on a website) is considered less of a security risk because the content is part of a greater document, and so scripting and CSS would not be unexpected.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] The MPEG-4 Part 20 standard – *Lightweight Application Scene Representation (LASeR) and Simple Aggregation Format (SAF)* is based on SVG Tiny.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] It was developed by MPEG (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC29/WG11) and published as ISO/IEC 14496-20:2006.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG capabilities are enhanced in MPEG-4 Part 20 with key features for mobile services, such as dynamic updates, binary encoding, state-of-art font representation.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] SVG was also accommodated in MPEG-4 Part 11, in the Extensible MPEG-4 Textual (XMT) format – a textual representation of the MPEG-4 multimedia content using XML.
[src:d3js/scalable-vector-graphics] While SVG has received widespread adoption in the market as the de-facto standard for scalable vector graphics, the files are still not natively supported in Windows, so users must download an SVG preview thumbnailer for the File Explorer or use an alternate file explorer with native support.
